The '''radix entomolaris''' is an additional root in human's [[mandibular]] [[molar (tooth)|molar]] teeth. The human mandibular teeth have two roots usually. In rare cases, however, a root may develop between the [[distal]] and the [[mesial]] roots which is called entomolaris, if it is located [[Anatomical terms of location#Teeth|lingual]] to the tooth. Such a phenomenon is named radix paramolaris in case an extra root is [[buccal space|buccal]] to a molar tooth.<ref>Chauhan, R., and S. Singh. "Endodontic treatment of mandibular molars with atypical root canal anatomy: reports of 4 cases." General dentistry 63.3 (2014): 67-70.</ref> It is important to remember that an extra root can appear both in the first and second molars.<ref>Ragavendran, N., Ganesh T. Bhat, and Mithra N. Hegde. "Mandibular second molar with 3 mesial canals and a radix paramolaris." Journal of pharmacy & bioallied sciences 6.Suppl 1 (2014): S182</ref><ref>Shemesh, Avi, et al. "Prevalence of 3-and 4-rooted First and Second Mandibular Molars in the Israeli Population." Journal of endodontics 41.3 (2015): 338-342.</ref><ref>Agarwal, Manoj, et al. "The Radix Entomolaris and Radix Paramolaris: An Endodontic Challenge." The journal of contemporary dental practice 15.4 (2014): 496.</ref><ref>Park, Jun-Beom, et al. "Evaluation of root anatomy of permanent mandibular premolars and molars in a Korean population with cone-beam computed tomography." European journal of dentistry 7.1 (2013): 94.</ref>

